    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A civil engineer designs a circular park plaza. A main fountain is placed at the exact center <m>O</m> of the plaza, and two decorative entrance gates are positioned at points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> along the outer circular walkway. A park bench is installed at point <m>P</m> on the far side of the outer walkway. If the angle measured from the bench to the gates is <m>\angle APB = 42^\circ</m>, calculate the angle <m>\angle AOB</m> formed from the center fountain to the two gates.</p>
            <figure xml:id="central-angle-park-plaza">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Central Fountain and Circumference Points ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Points positioned to mimic a standard inscribed/central angle problem
                \coordinate (A) at (220:2.5);
                \coordinate (B) at (340:2.5);
                \coordinate (P) at (100:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Walkway ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Angles (Fills & Arcs) ---
                % Inscribed angle at Bench P (42 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (P) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (P) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (P) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, below] at ($(P)+(270:0.6)$) {$42^{\circ}$};

                % Central angle at Fountain O (Angle AOB)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (O) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (O) circle (0.4);
                    \draw[red, thick] (O) circle (0.4);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below] at ($(O)+(280:0.6)$) {$\angle AOB$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Walkway Paths (Segments) ---
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (A);
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (B);
                \draw[thick] (P) -- (A);
                \draw[thick] (P) -- (B);

                % --- Step 5: Plot and Label Features ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {O/above, A/left, B/right, P/above} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Identify the applicable property: The angle subtended by an arc at the center of a circle is twice the angle subtended by the same arc at any point on the circumference.</p>
            <p>Set up the calculation using the given circumference angle:
                <me>\angle AOB = 2 \times \angle APB</me>
                <me>\angle AOB = 2 \times 42^\circ = 84^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>The angle formed from the center fountain to the gates measures <m>84^\circ</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>An architect plans a circular window frame with a straight steel structural support beam spanning across the center diameter from point <m>A</m> to point <m>B</m>. Two decorative framing bars connect points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> to a point <m>C</m> on the upper curved rim of the window. Determine the size of the structural joint angle <m>\angle ACB</m>.</p>
            <figure xml:id="angle-in-semicircle-window">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Points via Pure Angles ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Diameter endpoints spanning across the center
                \coordinate (A) at (180:2.5);
                \coordinate (B) at (0:2.5);
                
                % Point C on the upper curved rim
                \coordinate (C) at (65:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Window Frame ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angle (Thales's Theorem) ---
                % Angle ACB is an angle inscribed in a semicircle (90 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (C) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (C) circle (0.4);
                    \draw[red, thick] (C) circle (0.4);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below] at ($(C)+(245:0.6)$) {$\angle ACB$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Support Beams and Bars ---
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B); % Center diameter support beam
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (C); % Decorative framing bar
                \draw[thick] (B) -- (C); % Decorative framing bar

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {O/below, A/left, B/right, C/above} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Identify the applicable property: The angle subtended by a diameter at the circumference (an angle in a semicircle) is always a right angle.</p>
            <p>State the geometric deduction directly:
                <me>\angle ACB = 90^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>The structural joint angle at the window rim must be exactly <m>90^\circ</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A maritime radar station tracks ships using a circular display coordinate screen centered at point <m>O</m>. Two navigation buoys are fixed at perimeter coordinates <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>. A rescue vessel cruising along the outer boundary at point <m>W</m> measures its angle between the buoys as <m>\angle XWY = 53^\circ</m>. If a second patrol boat is stationed further down the outer boundary line at point <m>Z</m>, what is the measure of the angle <m>\angle XZY</m> between the same two buoys?</p>
            <figure xml:id="angles-in-same-segment-radar">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Perimeter Coordinates ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Base buoys fixed on the perimeter
                \coordinate (X) at (210:2.5);
                \coordinate (Y) at (330:2.5);
                
                % Ships stationed on the same major arc segment
                \coordinate (W) at (110:2.5);
                \coordinate (Z) at (50:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Screen Boundary ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles (Angles in Same Segment) ---
                % Angle XWY at rescue vessel W (53 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (W) -- (X) -- (Y) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (W) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (W) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, below] at ($(W)+(285:0.6)$) {$53^{\circ}$};

                % Angle XZY at patrol boat Z
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (Z) -- (X) -- (Y) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (Z) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[red, thick] (Z) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below left] at ($(Z)+(245:0.6)$) {$\angle XZY$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Visual Radar Tracking Lines ---
                \draw[thick] (X) -- (W) -- (Y);
                \draw[thick] (X) -- (Z) -- (Y);

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {O/below, X/left, Y/right, W/above, Z/above} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Identify the applicable property: Angles subtended by the same arc in the same segment of a circle are equal to one another.</p>
            <p>Equate the two circumference tracking angles directly:
                <me>\angle XZY = \angle XWY</me>
                <me>\angle XZY = 53^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>The angle monitored by the patrol boat at point <m>Z</m> is also <m>53^\circ</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A circular city traffic turntable routes cars through four intersection points labeled <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m>, and <m>S</m> sequentially, forming an embedded quadrilateral layout. An urban planner notices that the approach angle at intersection <m>P</m> measures <m>\angle QPS = 108^\circ</m>. Find the required clearance angle at the opposite intersection point <m>R</m>, denoted as <m>\angle QRS</m>.</p>
            <figure xml:id="cyclic-quad-traffic-turntable">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Points via Pure Angles ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Four intersection points forming a cyclic quadrilateral
                \coordinate (P) at (150:2.5);
                \coordinate (Q) at (60:2.5);
                \coordinate (R) at (320:2.5);
                \coordinate (S) at (230:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Traffic Turntable ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles ---
                % Approach angle at intersection P (108 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (P) -- (Q) -- (S) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (P) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (P) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, right] at ($(P)+(0:0.6)$) {$108^{\circ}$};

                % Clearance angle at opposite intersection R
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (R) -- (Q) -- (S) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (R) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[red, thick] (R) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, left] at ($(R)+(160:0.6)$) {$\angle QRS$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Road Layout Segments ---
                \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- (S) -- cycle;

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {P/left, Q/above, R/right, S/below left} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Identify the applicable property: The opposite interior angles of a cyclic quadrilateral are supplementary, meaning they add up to <m>180^\circ</m>.</p>
            <p>Set up the algebraic equation to find the missing angle:
                <me>\angle QPS + \angle QRS = 180^\circ</me>
                <me>108^\circ + \angle QRS = 180^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>Isolate and solve for the unknown angle:
                <me>\angle QRS = 180^\circ - 108^\circ = 72^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>The clearance angle at the opposite intersection must be <m>72^\circ</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A circular metal saw blade is divided into sectors for cooling ventilation slots. Three alignment rivets are stamped on the rim at positions <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>, with the central spindle hole located at point <m>O</m>. An engineer monitors the stamping process and notes that the central configuration angle is represented by <m>\angle AOB = 4x + 10^\circ</m>, while the outer rim angle is represented by <m>\angle ACB = 1x + 35^\circ</m>. Solve for the structural calibration variable <m>x</m>.</p>
            <figure xml:id="central-angle-saw-blade">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Rim Coordinates ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Alignment rivets on the outer rim
                \coordinate (A) at (210:2.5);
                \coordinate (B) at (330:2.5);
                \coordinate (C) at (90:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Saw Blade Rim ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles ---
                % Central spindle angle AOB
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (O) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (O) circle (0.4);
                    \draw[red, thick] (O) circle (0.4);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below] at ($(O)+(270:0.5)$) {$4x + 10^{\circ}$};

                % Outer rim angle ACB
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (C) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (C) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (C) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, below] at ($(C)+(270:0.6)$) {$1x + 35^{\circ}$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Connecting Structural Lines ---
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (A);
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (B);
                \draw[thick] (C) -- (A);
                \draw[thick] (C) -- (B);

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {O/above right, A/left, B/right, C/above} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Identify the applicable property: The central angle is twice the magnitude of the angle at the circumference sharing the same arc base.</p>
            <p>Set up the mathematical equation:
                <me>\angle AOB = 2 \times \angle ACB</me>
                <me>4x + 10^\circ = 2(1x + 35^\circ)</me>
            </p>
            <p>Expand the right side of the equation:
                <me>4x + 10^\circ = 2x + 70^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>Isolate the variable terms to find <m>x</m>:
                <me>4x - 2x = 70^\circ - 10^\circ</me>
                <me>2x = 60^\circ</me>
                <me>x = 30^\circ</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

