    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->
     <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A  crop-circle watering boom pivots around a center pump station <m>O</m>. Two sensor flags are placed at positions <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> on the outer perimeter rim. A drone hovering directly above an outer fence gate at point <m>P</m> measures an angle of <m>\angle APB = 37^\circ</m> between the flags. Calculate the layout angle <m>\angle AOB</m> radiating from the center pump station.</p>
                <figure xml:id="angle-at-center-watering-boom">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Perimeter Coordinates ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Sensor flags placed on the outer perimeter rim
                \coordinate (A) at (215:2.5);
                \coordinate (B) at (335:2.5);
                
                % Drone hovering directly above fence gate P
                \coordinate (P) at (105:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Perimeter Rim ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles ---
                % Inscribed angle at fence gate P (37 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (P) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (P) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (P) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, below] at ($(P)+(270:0.6)$) {$37^{\circ}$};

                % Layout angle radiating from the center pump station O
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (O) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (O) circle (0.4);
                    \draw[red, thick] (O) circle (0.4);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below] at ($(O)+(275:0.6)$) {$\angle AOB$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Framework Lines ---
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (A);
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (B);
                \draw[thick] (P) -- (A);
                \draw[thick] (P) -- (B);

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {O/above, A/left, B/right, P/above} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Using the angle-at-center theorem, the central angle is twice the circumference angle:</p>
                <p>
                    <me>\angle AOB = 2 \times \angle APB</me>
                    <me>\angle AOB = 2 \times 37^\circ = 74^\circ</me>
                    The center layout angle is <m>74^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A semicircular skateboard half-pipe is constructed with a flat coping deck edge extending as a diameter line from point <m>X</m> to point <m>Y</m>. A safety camera is anchored at point <m>Z</m> anywhere along the curved concrete bowl edge. What structural angle <m>\angle XZY</m> is formed by the sightlines from the camera to the two ends of the coping deck?</p>
                <figure xml:id="angle-in-semicircle-skateboard">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Points via Pure Angles ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Diameter lines for the flat coping deck edge
                \coordinate (X) at (180:2.5);
                \coordinate (Y) at (0:2.5);
                
                % Safety camera anchored along the curved concrete bowl edge
                \coordinate (Z) at (115:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Semicircular Half-Pipe Rim ---
                % Draws the lower semicircle path representing the bowl/half-pipe
                \draw[thick] (X) arc (180:360:2.5);
                % Draws the upper semicircle as a light or dashed line for completeness if needed, 
                % but since it is a half-pipe, we draw the solid upper arc where the camera sits.
                \draw[thick] (0:2.5) arc (0:180:2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angle (Thales's Theorem) ---
                % Angle XZY is an angle inscribed in a semicircle (90 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (Z) -- (X) -- (Y) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (Z) circle (0.4);
                    \draw[red, thick] (Z) circle (0.4);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below right] at ($(Z)+(295:0.5)$) {$\angle XZY$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Sightlines and Coping Deck ---
                \draw[thick] (X) -- (Y); % Flat coping deck edge (Diameter line)
                \draw[thick] (X) -- (Z); % Sightline from camera to end X
                \draw[thick] (Y) -- (Z); % Sightline from camera to end Y

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {X/left, Y/right, Z/above left} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Since the coping deck line forms a true circle diameter, any angle drawn from its endpoints to the curved perimeter boundary forms an angle in a semicircle:</p>
                <p>
                    <me>\angle XZY = 90^\circ</me>
                    The camera sightline forms a perfect <m>90^\circ</m> right angle.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A circle theater balcony stage setup has two primary sound speakers mounted at perimeter points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. A sound check technician at seat location <m>M</m> along the back wall measures an audio spread angle of <m>\angle AMB = 48^\circ</m>. If the technician moves to seat location <m>N</m> further along the same continuous wall arc segment, what sound spread angle <m>\angle ANB</m> will they experience?</p>
                <figure xml:id="angles-same-segment-theater">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Perimeter Coordinates ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Primary sound speakers mounted at perimeter points
                \coordinate (A) at (210:2.5);
                \coordinate (B) at (330:2.5);
                
                % Seat locations along the continuous back wall arc segment
                \coordinate (M) at (115:2.5);
                \coordinate (N) at (55:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Semicircular/Circular Balcony Rim ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles ---
                % Audio spread angle at seat location M (48 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (M) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (M) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (M) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, below] at ($(M)+(280:0.6)$) {$48^{\circ}$};

                % Audio spread angle at seat location N
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (N) -- (A) -- (B) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (N) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[red, thick] (N) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below left] at ($(N)+(245:0.6)$) {$\angle ANB$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Sound Trajectory Sightlines ---
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (M) -- (B);
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (N) -- (B);

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {A/left, B/right, M/above, N/above} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Angles subtended by the same arc in the same circular segment are uniform:</p>
                <p>
                    <me>\angle ANB = \angle AMB = 48^\circ</me>
                    The spread angle remains exactly <m>48^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A circular wall clock has four electrical terminals installed on its rim casing at points <m>K</m>, <m>L</m>, <m>M</m>, and <m>N</m> sequentially to manage wiring paths. If the internal component angle at terminal <m>L</m> measures <m>\angle KNM = 115^\circ</m>, calculate the required structural angle at the opposite terminal <m>L</m>, denoted as <m>\angle KLM</m>.</p>
                <figure xml:id="cyclic-quad-wall-clock">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Points via Pure Angles ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Four electrical terminals forming a cyclic quadrilateral sequentially
                \coordinate (K) at (120:2.5);
                \coordinate (L) at (40:2.5);
                \coordinate (M) at (300:2.5);
                \coordinate (N) at (210:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Wall Clock Casing ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles ---
                % Internal component angle at terminal N (115 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (N) -- (K) -- (M) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (N) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (N) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, right] at ($(N)+(15:0.6)$) {$115^{\circ}$};

                % Structural angle at the opposite terminal L
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (L) -- (K) -- (M) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (L) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[red, thick] (L) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, left] at ($(L)+(190:0.6)$) {$\angle KLM$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Wiring Path Segments ---
                \draw[thick] (K) -- (L) -- (M) -- (N) -- cycle;

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {K/above left, L/above right, M/below right, N/left} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The four casing terminals form an embedded cyclic quadrilateral. Opposite interior angles must sum to <m>180^\circ</m>:</p>
                <p>
                    <me>\angle KLM + \angle KNM = 180^\circ</me>
                    <me>\angle KLM + 115^\circ = 180^\circ</me>
                    <me>\angle KLM = 180^\circ - 115^\circ = 65^\circ</me>
                    The opposite terminal angle measures <m>65^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A  wheel with a center axle axis point <m>O</m> has structural support pins at positions <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> on its outer track. A passenger boarding car is located at point <m>R</m> on the top rim. An engineer notices the system alignment equations state that central axle angle <m>\angle POQ = 6x + 20^\circ</m> and the top car angle <m>\angle PRQ = 2x + 25^\circ</m>. Find the alignment variable value for <m>x</m>.</p>
                <figure xml:id="central-angle-wheel-alignment">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Track Coordinates ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Structural support pins on the outer track
                \coordinate (P) at (220:2.5);
                \coordinate (Q) at (320:2.5);
                
                % Passenger boarding car located on the top rim
                \coordinate (R) at (85:2.5);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Wheel Track ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles ---
                % Central axle angle POQ
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (O) -- (P) -- (Q) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (O) circle (0.4);
                    \draw[red, thick] (O) circle (0.4);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, below] at ($(O)+(270:0.5)$) {$6x + 20^{\circ}$};

                % Top car angle PRQ
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (R) -- (P) -- (Q) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (R) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (R) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, below] at ($(R)+(270:0.6)$) {$2x + 25^{\circ}$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Structural Connections ---
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (P);
                \draw[thick] (O) -- (Q);
                \draw[thick] (R) -- (P);
                \draw[thick] (R) -- (Q);

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {O/above right, P/left, Q/right, R/above} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Set up the relationship where the central axle angle equals twice the upper rim boundary angle:</p>
                <p>
                    <me>\angle POQ = 2 \times \angle PRQ</me>
                    <me>6x + 20^\circ = 2(2x + 25^\circ)</me>
                </p>
                <p>Expand and solve the algebraic linear equation:
                    <me>6x + 20^\circ = 4x + 50^\circ</me>
                    <me>6x - 4x = 50^\circ - 20^\circ</me>
                    <me>2x = 30^\circ \implies x = 15^\circ</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A corporate logo layout circular in shape connects four brand icon hubs along its outer rim boundary at positions <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>D</m> sequentially. The graphic designer extends the straight base boundary line segment <m>AB</m> past hub <m>B</m> to an external alignment point <m>E</m> to guide an accent banner. If the interior opposite icon hub angle measures <m>\angle ADC = 82^\circ</m>, evaluate the measure of the exterior layout angle <m>\angle CBE</m>.</p>
                <figure xml:id="cyclic-quad-corporate-logo">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                % --- Step 1: Define Center and Points via Pure Angles ---
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                
                % Four brand icon hubs along the rim boundary sequentially
                \coordinate (A) at (200:2.5);
                \coordinate (B) at (320:2.5);
                \coordinate (C) at (50:2.5);
                \coordinate (D) at (120:2.5);
                
                % Extension point E along the line AB past hub B
                \coordinate (E) at ($(B) + (20:1.2)$);

                % --- Step 2: Draw the Circular Logo Layout ---
                \draw[thick] (O) circle (2.5);
                
                % --- Step 3: Draw Highlighted Angles ---
                % Interior opposite icon hub angle at D (82 degrees)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (D) -- (A) -- (C) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (D) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[blue, thick] (D) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[blue, above] at ($(D)+(280:0.6)$) {$82^{\circ}$};

                % Exterior layout angle at B (Angle CBE)
                \begin{scope}
                    \clip (B) -- (C) -- (E) -- cycle;
                    \draw[draw=none, fill=red!20, opacity=0.6] (B) circle (0.5);
                    \draw[red, thick] (B) circle (0.5);
                \end{scope}
                \node[red, right] at ($(B)+(40:0.6)$) {$\angle CBE$};

                % --- Step 4: Draw Framework and Extension Lines ---
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick, dashed] (B) -- (E); 

                % --- Step 5: Points and Labels ---
                \foreach \pt/\pos in {A/left, B/below, C/right, D/above, E/right} {
                    \fill (\pt) circle (2pt);
                    \node[\pos] at (\pt) {$\pt$};
                }
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>By applying the exterior angle theorem of a cyclic quadrilateral, the exterior angle created by extending a side is equal to the interior opposite angle across the layout:</p>
                <p>
                    <me>\angle CBE = \angle ADC</me>
                    <me>\angle CBE = 82^\circ</me>
                    The exterior accent alignment angle is <m>82^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

